\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f0\fs22\lang10 Fields Overview\par
Fields are the building blocks of Payload. They define the schema of the Documents that will be stored in the Database, as well as automatically generate the corresponding UI within the Admin Panel.\par
\par
There are many Field Types to choose from, ranging anywhere from simple text strings to nested arrays and blocks. Most fields save data to the database, while others are strictly presentational. Fields can have Custom Validations, Conditional Logic, Access Control, Hooks, and so much more.\par
\par
Fields can be endlessly customized in their appearance and behavior without affecting their underlying data structure. Fields are designed to withstand heavy modification or even complete replacement through the use of Custom Field Components.\par
\par
To configure fields, use the fields property in your Collection or Global config:\par
\par
import type \{ CollectionConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const Page: CollectionConfig = \{\par
  // ...\par
  fields: [\par
    \par
    // ...\par
  ],\par
\}\par
Field Types\par
Payload provides a wide variety of built-in Field Types, each with its own unique properties and behaviors that determine which values it can accept, how it is presented in the API, and how it will be rendered in the Admin Panel.\par
\par
To configure fields, use the fields property in your Collection or Global config:\par
\par
import type \{ CollectionConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const Page: CollectionConfig = \{\par
  slug: 'pages',\par
  fields: [\par
    \{\par
      name: 'field',\par
      type: 'text',\par
    \},\par
  ],\par
\}\par
Reminder: Each field is an object with at least the type property. This matches the field to its corresponding Field Type. More details.\par
\par
There are three main categories of fields in Payload:\par
\par
Data Fields\par
Presentational Fields\par
Virtual Fields\par
To begin writing fields, first determine which Field Type best supports your application. Then author your field accordingly using the Field Options for your chosen field type.\par
\par
Data Fields\par
Data Fields are used to store data in the Database. All Data Fields have a name property. This is the key that will be used to store the field's value.\par
\par
Here are the available Data Fields:\par
\par
Array - for repeating content, supports nested fields\par
Blocks - for block-based content, supports nested fields\par
Checkbox - saves boolean true / false values\par
Code - renders a code editor interface that saves a string\par
Date - renders a date picker and saves a timestamp\par
Email - ensures the value is a properly formatted email address\par
Group - nests fields within a keyed object\par
JSON - renders a JSON editor interface that saves a JSON object\par
Number - saves numeric values\par
Point - for location data, saves geometric coordinates\par
Radio - renders a radio button group that allows only one value to be selected\par
Relationship - assign relationships to other collections\par
Rich Text - renders a fully extensible rich text editor\par
Select - renders a dropdown / picklist style value selector\par
Tabs (Named) - similar to group, but renders nested fields within a tabbed layout\par
Text - simple text input that saves a string\par
Textarea - similar to text, but allows for multi-line input\par
Upload - allows local file and image upload\par
Presentational Fields\par
Presentational Fields do not store data in the database. Instead, they are used to organize and present other fields in the Admin Panel, or to add custom UI components.\par
\par
Here are the available Presentational Fields:\par
\par
Collapsible - nests fields within a collapsible component\par
Row - aligns fields horizontally\par
Tabs (Unnamed) - nests fields within a tabbed layout. It is not presentational if the tab has a name.\par
Group (Unnamed) - nests fields within a keyed object. It is not presentational if the group has a name.\par
UI - blank field for custom UI components\par
Virtual Fields\par
Virtual fields display data that is not stored in the database, but is computed or derived from other fields.\par
\par
Here are the available Virtual Fields:\par
\par
Join - achieves two-way data binding between fields\par
Tip: Don't see a built-in field type that you need? Build it! Using a combination of Field Validations and Custom Components, you can override the entirety of how a component functions within the Admin Panel to effectively create your own field type.\par
\par
Virtual Field Configuration\par
While Join fields are purpose-built virtual field types, any field type can be made virtual by adding the virtual property to its configuration. This allows you to create computed or relationship-derived fields that appear in API responses without being stored in the database.\par
\par
Virtual fields are populated during API responses and can be used in the Admin Panel, but their values are not persisted to the database. This makes them ideal for displaying read-only computed data, relationship summaries, or formatted versions of existing field data.\par
\par
Configuring Virtual Fields\par
Any field type can be made virtual by adding the virtual property to the field configuration. The virtual property can be configured in two ways:\par
\par
Boolean Virtual Fields\par
When virtual is set to true, the field becomes virtual but doesn't automatically populate any data. You'll typically use Field-level Hooks to compute and populate the field's value:\par
\par
\{\par
  name: 'fullName',\par
  type: 'text',\par
  virtual: true,\par
  hooks: \{\par
    afterRead: [\par
      (\{ siblingData \}) => \{\par
        return `$\{siblingData.firstName\} $\{siblingData.lastName\}`\par
      \}\par
    ]\par
  \}\par
\}\par
String Path Virtual Fields\par
When virtual is set to a string path, it creates a "virtual relationship field" that automatically resolves to data from another field in the document. This is particularly useful for displaying relationship data:\par
\par
\{\par
  name: 'authorName',\par
  type: 'text',\par
  virtual: 'author.name' // Resolves to the 'name' field of the 'author' relationship\par
\}\par
Virtual Path Syntax\par
Virtual paths use dot notation to traverse relationships and nested data:\par
\par
author.name - Gets the name field from the author relationship\par
author.profile.bio - Gets the bio field from a nested profile object within the author relationship\par
categories.title - For hasMany relationships, returns an array of title values\par
request.additionalStakeholders.email - Traverses multiple relationship levels\par
Important Requirements for Virtual Path Fields:\par
\par
Source Relationship Required: The document must have a relationship field that corresponds to the first part of the virtual path. For example, if using virtual: 'author.name', there must be an author relationship field defined in the same collection.\par
Path Resolution: Virtual paths resolve at query time by following the relationships and extracting the specified field values.\par
Array Handling: When the virtual path traverses a hasMany relationship, the result will be an array of values.\par
Common Use Cases\par
Displaying Relationship Names\par
Instead of just showing relationship IDs, display the actual names or titles:\par
\par
// Original relationship field\par
\{\par
  name: 'author',\par
  type: 'relationship',\par
  relationTo: 'users'\par
\},\par
// Virtual field to display author's name\par
\{\par
  name: 'authorName',\par
  type: 'text',\par
  virtual: 'author.name'\par
\}\par
Multiple Relationship Values\par
For hasMany relationships, virtual fields return arrays:\par
\par
// Original relationship field\par
\{\par
  name: 'categories',\par
  type: 'relationship',\par
  relationTo: 'categories',\par
  hasMany: true\par
\},\par
// Virtual field to display category titles\par
\{\par
  name: 'categoryTitles',\par
  type: 'text',\par
  virtual: 'categories.title' // Returns ['Tech', 'News', 'Updates']\par
\}\par
Computed Values\par
Use hooks to create computed virtual fields:\par
\par
\{\par
  name: 'wordCount',\par
  type: 'number',\par
  virtual: true,\par
  hooks: \{\par
    afterRead: [\par
      (\{ siblingData \}) => \{\par
        const content = siblingData.content || ''\par
        return content.split(/\\s+/).length\par
      \}\par
    ]\par
  \}\par
\}\par
Virtual Fields in API Responses\par
Virtual fields appear in API responses alongside regular fields:\par
\par
\{\par
  "id": "123",\par
  "title": "My Post",\par
  "author": "64f1234567890abcdef12345",\par
  "authorName": "John Doe", // Virtual field\par
  "categories": ["64f9876543210fedcba67890", "64f5432109876543210abcdef"],\par
  "categoryTitles": ["Tech", "News"], // Virtual field\par
  "wordCount": 450 // Virtual field\par
\}\par
Important: When using virtual path fields, ensure that the referenced relationship field exists in your schema. Virtual paths like author.name require an author relationship field to be defined, otherwise the virtual field will not resolve properly.\par
\par
Field Options\par
All fields require at least the type property. This matches the field to its corresponding Field Type to determine its appearance and behavior within the Admin Panel. Each Field Type has its own unique set of options based on its own type.\par
\par
To set a field's type, use the type property in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ Field \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const MyField: Field = \{\par
  type: 'text', \par
  name: 'myField',\par
\}\par
For a full list of configuration options, see the documentation for each Field Type.\par
\par
Field Names\par
All Data Fields require a name property. This is the key that will be used to store and retrieve the field's value in the database. This property must be unique amongst this field's siblings.\par
\par
To set a field's name, use the name property in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ Field \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const MyField: Field = \{\par
  type: 'text',\par
  name: 'myField', \par
\}\par
Since field names map directly to keys in API response objects and to column names in the database, they should follow JavaScript identifier conventions: start with a letter or underscore, and contain only letters, numbers, and underscores. Just like all Payload field names are strings, all Payload response objects use strings as their keys \f1\emdash  so treat field names as you would a JavaScript variable name.\par
\par
Avoid field names that start with a digit (e.g. '1', '2field') or contain hyphens (e.g. 'field-name'). While these are valid strings in TypeScript, they can cause unexpected behavior when Payload accesses data using dot-notation paths, generates GraphQL schemas, or maps fields to database columns. GraphQL identifiers do not allow hyphens, so hyphenated field names will cause schema generation to fail.\par
\par
Payload reserves various field names for internal use. Using reserved field names will result in your field being sanitized from the config.\par
\par
The following field names are forbidden and cannot be used:\par
\par
__v\par
salt\par
hash\par
file\par
status - with Postgres Adapter and when drafts are enabled\par
Field-level Hooks\par
In addition to being able to define Hooks on a document-level, you can define extremely granular logic field-by-field.\par
\par
To define Field-level Hooks, use the hooks property in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ Field \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const MyField: Field = \{\par
  type: 'text',\par
  name: 'myField',\par
  hooks: \{\par
    // ...\par
  \},\par
\}\par
For full details on Field-level Hooks, see the Field Hooks documentation.\par
\par
Field-level Access Control\par
In addition to being able to define Access Control on a document-level, you can define extremely granular permissions field-by-field.\par
\par
To define Field-level Access Control, use the access property in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ Field \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const MyField: Field = \{\par
  type: 'text',\par
  name: 'myField',\par
  access: \{\par
    // ...\par
  \},\par
\}\par
For full details on Field-level Access Control, see the Field Access Control documentation.\par
\par
Default Values\par
Fields can be optionally prefilled with initial values. This is used in both the Admin Panel as well as API requests to populate missing or undefined field values during the create or update operations.\par
\par
To set a field's default value, use the defaultValue property in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ Field \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const MyField: Field = \{\par
  type: 'text',\par
  name: 'myField',\par
  defaultValue: 'Hello, World!', \par
\}\par
Default values can be defined as a static value or a function that returns a value. When a defaultValue is defined statically, Payload's Database Adapters will apply it to the database schema or models.\par
\par
Functions can be written to make use of the following argument properties:\par
\par
user - the authenticated user object\par
locale - the currently selected locale string\par
req - the PayloadRequest object\par
Here is an example of a defaultValue function:\par
\par
import type \{ Field \} from 'payload'\par
\par
const translation: \{\par
  en: 'Written by'\par
  es: 'Escrito por'\par
\}\par
\par
export const myField: Field = \{\par
  name: 'attribution',\par
  type: 'text',\par
  defaultValue: (\{ user, locale, req \}) =>\par
    `$\{translation[locale]\} $\{user.name\}`,\par
\}\par
Tip: You can use async defaultValue functions to fill fields with data from API requests or Local API using req.payload.\par
\par
Validation\par
Fields are automatically validated based on their Field Type and other Field Options such as required or min and max value constraints. If needed, however, field validations can be customized or entirely replaced by providing your own custom validation functions.\par
\par
To set a custom field validation function, use the validate property in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ Field \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const MyField: Field = \{\par
  type: 'text',\par
  name: 'myField',\par
  validate: (value) => Boolean(value) || 'This field is required', \par
\}\par
Custom validation functions should return either true or a string representing the error message to display in API responses.\par
\par
The following arguments are provided to the validate function:\par
\par
Argument\par
\par
Description\par
\par
value\par
\par
The value of the field being validated.\par
\par
ctx\par
\par
An object with additional data and context. More details\par
\par
Validation Context\par
The ctx argument contains full document data, sibling field data, the current operation, and other useful information such as currently authenticated user:\par
\par
import type \{ Field \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const MyField: Field = \{\par
  type: 'text',\par
  name: 'myField',\par
  validate: (val, \{ user \}) =>\par
    Boolean(user) || 'You must be logged in to save this field',\par
\}\par
The following additional properties are provided in the ctx object:\par
\par
Property\par
\par
Description\par
\par
data\par
\par
An object containing the full collection or global document currently being edited.\par
\par
siblingData\par
\par
An object containing document data that is scoped to only fields within the same parent of this field.\par
\par
operation\par
\par
Will be create or update depending on the UI action or API call.\par
\par
path\par
\par
The full path to the field in the schema, represented as an array of string segments, including array indexes. I.e ['group', 'myArray', '1', 'textField'].\par
\par
id\par
\par
The id of the current document being edited. id is undefined during the create operation.\par
\par
req\par
\par
The current HTTP request object. Contains payload, user, etc.\par
\par
event\par
\par
Either onChange or submit depending on the current action. Used as a performance opt-in. More details.\par
\par
Localized and Built-in Error Messages\par
You can return localized error messages by utilizing the translation function provided in the req object:\par
\par
import type \{ Field \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const MyField: Field = \{\par
  type: 'text',\par
  name: 'myField',\par
  validate: (value, \{ req: \{ t \} \}) =>\par
    Boolean(value) || t('validation:required'), \par
\}\par
This way you can use Custom Translations as well as Payload's built in error messages (like validation:required used in the example above). For a full list of available translation strings, see the english translation file of Payload.\par
\par
Reusing Default Field Validations\par
When using custom validation functions, Payload will use yours in place of the default. However, you might want to simply augment the default validation with your own custom logic.\par
\par
To reuse default field validations, call them from within your custom validation function:\par
\par
import \{ text \} from 'payload/shared'\par
\par
const field: Field = \{\par
  name: 'notBad',\par
  type: 'text',\par
  validate: (val, args) => \{\par
    if (val === 'bad') return 'This cannot be "bad"'\par
    return text(val, args) \par
  \},\par
\}\par
Here is a list of all default field validation functions:\par
\par
import \{\par
  array,\par
  blocks,\par
  checkbox,\par
  code,\par
  date,\par
  email,\par
  json,\par
  number,\par
  point,\par
  radio,\par
  relationship,\par
  richText,\par
  select,\par
  tabs,\par
  text,\par
  textarea,\par
  upload,\par
\} from 'payload/shared'\par
Validation Performance\par
When writing async or computationally heavy validation functions, it is important to consider the performance implications. Within the Admin Panel, validations are executed on every change to the field, so they should be as lightweight as possible and only run when necessary.\par
\par
If you need to perform expensive validations, such as querying the database, consider using the event property in the ctx object to only run that particular validation on form submission.\par
\par
To write asynchronous validation functions, use the async keyword to define your function:\par
\par
import type \{ CollectionConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const Orders: CollectionConfig = \{\par
  slug: 'orders',\par
  fields: [\par
    \{\par
      name: 'customerNumber',\par
      type: 'text',\par
      validate: async (val, \{ event \}) => \{\par
        if (event === 'onChange') \{\par
          return true\par
        \}\par
\par
        // only perform expensive validation when the form is submitted\par
        const response = await fetch(`https://your-api.com/customers/$\{val\}`)\par
\par
        if (response.ok) \{\par
          return true\par
        \}\par
\par
        return 'The customer number provided does not match any customers within our records.'\par
      \},\par
    \},\par
  ],\par
\}\par
For more performance tips, see the Performance documentation.\par
\par
Custom ID Fields\par
All Collections automatically generate their own ID field. If needed, you can override this behavior by providing an explicit ID field to your config. This field should either be required or have a hook to generate the ID dynamically.\par
\par
To define a custom ID field, add a top-level field with the name property set to id:\par
\par
import type \{ CollectionConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const MyCollection: CollectionConfig = \{\par
  // ...\par
  fields: [\par
    \{\par
      name: 'id', \par
      required: true,\par
      type: 'number',\par
    \},\par
  ],\par
\}\par
Reminder: The Custom ID Fields can only be of type Number or Text. Custom ID fields with type text must not contain / or . characters.\par
\par
Admin Options\par
You can customize the appearance and behavior of fields within the Admin Panel through the admin property of any Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ CollectionConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const CollectionConfig: CollectionConfig = \{\par
  // ...\par
  fields: [\par
    // ...\par
    \{\par
      name: 'myField',\par
      type: 'text',\par
      admin: \{\par
        \par
        // ...\par
      \},\par
    \},\par
  ],\par
\}\par
The following options are available:\par
\par
Option\par
\par
Description\par
\par
condition\par
\par
Programmatically show / hide fields based on other fields. More details.\par
\par
components\par
\par
All Field Components can be swapped out for Custom Components that you define.\par
\par
description\par
\par
Helper text to display alongside the field to provide more information for the editor. More details.\par
\par
position\par
\par
Use 'sidebar' to render the field in the sidebar or 'main' (default) to keep it in the main area.\par
\par
width\par
\par
Restrict the width of a field. You can pass any string-based value here, be it pixels, percentages, etc. This property is especially useful when fields are nested within a Row type where they can be organized horizontally.\par
\par
style\par
\par
CSS Properties to inject into the root element of the field.\par
\par
className\par
\par
Attach a CSS class attribute to the root DOM element of a field.\par
\par
readOnly\par
\par
Setting a field to readOnly has no effect on the API whatsoever but disables the admin component's editability to prevent editors from modifying the field's value.\par
\par
disabled\par
\par
If a field is disabled, it is completely omitted from the Admin Panel entirely.\par
\par
disableBulkEdit\par
\par
Set disableBulkEdit to true to prevent fields from appearing in the select options when making edits for multiple documents. Defaults to true for UI fields.\par
\par
disableGroupBy\par
\par
Set disableGroupBy to true to prevent fields from appearing in the list view groupBy options. Defaults to false.\par
\par
disableListColumn\par
\par
Set disableListColumn to true to prevent fields from appearing in the list view column selector. Defaults to false.\par
\par
disableListFilter\par
\par
Set disableListFilter to true to prevent fields from appearing in the list view filter options. Defaults to false.\par
\par
hidden\par
\par
Will transform the field into a hidden input type. Its value will still submit with requests in the Admin Panel, but the field itself will not be visible to editors.\par
\par
Field Descriptions\par
Field Descriptions are used to provide additional information to the editor about a field, such as special instructions. Their placement varies from field to field, but typically are displayed with subtle style differences beneath the field inputs.\par
\par
A description can be configured in three ways:\par
\par
As a string.\par
As a function which returns a string. More details.\par
As a React component. More details.\par
To add a Custom Description to a field, use the admin.description property in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ CollectionConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const MyCollectionConfig: CollectionConfig = \{\par
  // ...\par
  fields: [\par
    // ...\par
    \{\par
      name: 'myField',\par
      type: 'text',\par
      admin: \{\par
        description: 'Hello, world!', \par
      \},\par
    \},\par
  ],\par
\}\par
Reminder: To replace the Field Description with a Custom Component, use the admin.components.Description property. More details.\par
\par
Description Functions\par
Custom Descriptions can also be defined as a function. Description Functions are executed on the server and can be used to format simple descriptions based on the user's current Locale.\par
\par
To add a Description Function to a field, set the admin.description property to a function in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ CollectionConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const MyCollectionConfig: CollectionConfig = \{\par
  // ...\par
  fields: [\par
    // ...\par
    \{\par
      name: 'myField',\par
      type: 'text',\par
      admin: \{\par
        description: (\{ t \}) => `$\{t('Hello, world!')\}`, \par
      \},\par
    \},\par
  ],\par
\}\par
All Description Functions receive the following arguments:\par
\par
Argument\par
\par
Description\par
\par
t\par
\par
The t function used to internationalize the Admin Panel. More details\par
\par
Note: If you need to subscribe to live updates within your form, use a Description Component instead. More details.\par
\par
Conditional Logic\par
You can show and hide fields based on what other fields are doing by utilizing conditional logic on a field by field basis. The condition property on a field's admin config accepts a function which takes the following arguments:\par
\par
Argument\par
\par
Description\par
\par
data\par
\par
The entire document's data that is currently being edited.\par
\par
siblingData\par
\par
Only the fields that are direct siblings to the field with the condition.\par
\par
ctx\par
\par
An object containing additional information about the field\rquote s location and user.\par
\par
The ctx object:\par
\par
Property\par
\par
Description\par
\par
blockData\par
\par
The nearest parent block's data. If the field is not inside a block, this will be undefined.\par
\par
operation\par
\par
A string relating to which operation the field type is currently executing within.\par
\par
path\par
\par
The full path to the field in the schema, represented as an array of string segments, including array indexes. I.e ['group', 'myArray', '1', 'textField'].\par
\par
user\par
\par
The currently authenticated user object.\par
\par
The condition function should return a boolean that will control if the field should be displayed or not.\par
\par
Example:\par
\par
\{\par
  fields: [\par
    \{\par
      name: 'enableGreeting',\par
      type: 'checkbox',\par
      defaultValue: false,\par
    \},\par
    \{\par
      name: 'greeting',\par
      type: 'text',\par
      admin: \{\par
        condition: (data, siblingData, \{ blockData, path, user \}) => \{\par
          if (data.enableGreeting) \{\par
            return true\par
          \} else \{\par
            return false\par
          \}\par
        \},\par
      \},\par
    \},\par
  ]\par
\}\par
Custom Components\par
Within the Admin Panel, fields are represented in three distinct places:\par
\par
Field - The actual form field rendered in the Edit View.\par
Cell - The table cell component rendered in the List View.\par
Filter - The filter component rendered in the List View.\par
Diff - The Diff component rendered in the Version Diff View\par
To swap in Field Components with your own, use the admin.components property in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ CollectionConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const CollectionConfig: CollectionConfig = \{\par
  // ...\par
  fields: [\par
    // ...\par
    \{\par
      // ...\par
      admin: \{\par
        components: \{\par
          \par
          // ...\par
        \},\par
      \},\par
    \},\par
  ],\par
\}\par
The following options are available:\par
\par
Component\par
\par
Description\par
\par
Field\par
\par
The form field rendered of the Edit View. More details.\par
\par
Cell\par
\par
The table cell rendered of the List View. More details.\par
\par
Filter\par
\par
The filter component rendered in the List View. More details.\par
\par
Label\par
\par
Override the default Label of the Field Component. More details.\par
\par
Error\par
\par
Override the default Error of the Field Component. More details.\par
\par
Diff\par
\par
Override the default Diff component rendered in the Version Diff View. More details.\par
\par
Description\par
\par
Override the default Description of the Field Component. More details.\par
\par
beforeInput\par
\par
An array of elements that will be added before the input of the Field Component. More details.\par
\par
afterInput\par
\par
An array of elements that will be added after the input of the Field Component. More details.\par
\par
Field\par
The Field Component is the actual form field rendered in the Edit View. This is the input that user's will interact with when editing a document.\par
\par
To swap in your own Field Component, use the admin.components.Field property in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ CollectionConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const CollectionConfig: CollectionConfig = \{\par
  // ...\par
  fields: [\par
    // ...\par
    \{\par
      // ...\par
      admin: \{\par
        components: \{\par
          Field: '/path/to/MyFieldComponent', \par
        \},\par
      \},\par
    \},\par
  ],\par
\}\par
For details on how to build Custom Components, see Building Custom Components.\par
\par
Instead of replacing the entire Field Component, you can alternately replace or slot-in only specific parts by using the Label, Error, beforeInput, and afterInput properties.\par
\par
Default Props\par
All Field Components receive the following props by default:\par
\par
Property\par
\par
Description\par
\par
docPreferences\par
\par
An object that contains the Preferences for the document.\par
\par
field\par
\par
In Client Components, this is the sanitized Client Field Config. In Server Components, this is the original Field Config. Server Components will also receive the sanitized field config through theclientField prop (see below).\par
\par
locale\par
\par
The locale of the field. More details.\par
\par
readOnly\par
\par
A boolean value that represents if the field is read-only or not.\par
\par
user\par
\par
The currently authenticated user. More details.\par
\par
validate\par
\par
A function that can be used to validate the field.\par
\par
path\par
\par
A string representing the direct, dynamic path to the field at runtime, i.e. myGroup.myArray.0.myField.\par
\par
schemaPath\par
\par
A string representing the direct, static path to the Field Config, i.e. posts.myGroup.myArray.myField.\par
\par
indexPath\par
\par
A hyphen-notated string representing the path to the field within the nearest named ancestor field, i.e. 0-0\par
\par
In addition to the above props, all Server Components will also receive the following props:\par
\par
Property\par
\par
Description\par
\par
clientField\par
\par
The serializable Client Field Config.\par
\par
field\par
\par
The Field Config.\par
\par
data\par
\par
The current document being edited.\par
\par
i18n\par
\par
The i18n object.\par
\par
payload\par
\par
The Payload class.\par
\par
permissions\par
\par
The field permissions based on the currently authenticated user.\par
\par
siblingData\par
\par
The data of the field's siblings.\par
\par
user\par
\par
The currently authenticated user. More details.\par
\par
value\par
\par
The value of the field at render-time.\par
\par
Sending and receiving values from the form\par
When swapping out the Field component, you are responsible for sending and receiving the field's value from the form itself.\par
\par
To do so, import the useField hook from @payloadcms/ui and use it to manage the field's value:\par
\par
'use client'\par
import \{ useField \} from '@payloadcms/ui'\par
\par
export const CustomTextField: React.FC = () => \{\par
  const \{ value, setValue \} = useField() \par
\par
  return <input onChange=\{(e) => setValue(e.target.value)\} value=\{value\} />\par
\}\par
For a complete list of all available React hooks, see the Payload React Hooks documentation. For additional help, see Building Custom Components.\par
\par
TypeScript\par
When building Custom Field Components, you can import the client field props to ensure type safety in your component. There is an explicit type for the Field Component, one for every Field Type and server/client environment. The convention is to prepend the field type onto the target type, i.e. TextFieldClientComponent:\par
\par
import type \{\par
  TextFieldClientComponent,\par
  TextFieldServerComponent,\par
  TextFieldClientProps,\par
  TextFieldServerProps,\par
  // ...and so on for each Field Type\par
\} from 'payload'\par
See each individual Field Type for exact type imports.\par
\par
Cell\par
The Cell Component is rendered in the table of the List View. It represents the value of the field when displayed in a table cell.\par
\par
To swap in your own Cell Component, use the admin.components.Cell property in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ Field \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const myField: Field = \{\par
  name: 'myField',\par
  type: 'text',\par
  admin: \{\par
    components: \{\par
      Cell: '/path/to/MyCustomCellComponent', \par
    \},\par
  \},\par
\}\par
Example: Custom Cell Component\par
'use client'\par
import type \{ DefaultCellComponentProps \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const MyCustomCellComponent: React.FC<DefaultCellComponentProps> = (\{\par
  cellData,\par
  field,\par
  rowData,\par
\}) => \{\par
  const price = cellData as number\par
  const currency = rowData.currency || 'USD'\par
\par
  return (\par
    <span>\par
      \{new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', \{\par
        style: 'currency',\par
        currency,\par
      \}).format(price)\}\par
    </span>\par
  )\par
\}\par
Important: Use DefaultCellComponentProps for client components (with 'use client' directive) and DefaultServerCellComponentProps for server components. Omitting 'use client' will change the expected prop types.\par
\par
All Cell Components receive the following props:\par
\par
Property\par
\par
Description\par
\par
cellData\par
\par
The data value for this specific cell.\par
\par
collectionSlug\par
\par
The slug of the collection being rendered.\par
\par
field\par
\par
The field configuration object.\par
\par
rowData\par
\par
An object containing all data for the current row.\par
\par
className\par
\par
Optional CSS class name for styling the cell.\par
\par
columnIndex\par
\par
Optional index number of the column.\par
\par
customCellProps\par
\par
Optional additional custom props passed to the cell.\par
\par
link\par
\par
Optional boolean representing whether this cell should be wrapped in a link.\par
\par
linkURL\par
\par
Optional URL string for the link.\par
\par
onClick\par
\par
Optional function called when the cell is clicked.\par
\par
viewType\par
\par
Optional string representing the type of view being rendered.\par
\par
Note: Cell components receive a different set of props than Field components, optimized specifically for rendering data in the List View. They do not receive the standard Field component props like docPreferences, validate, or path.\par
\par
For details on how to build Custom Components themselves, see Building Custom Components.\par
\par
Filter\par
The Filter Component is the actual input element rendered within the "Filter By" dropdown of the List View used to represent this field when building filters.\par
\par
All Custom Filter Components receive the following props:\par
\par
Property\par
\par
Description\par
\par
disabled\par
\par
Boolean indicating whether the filter is disabled.\par
\par
onChange\par
\par
Function to call when the filter value changes.\par
\par
operator\par
\par
The comparison operator being used for the filter.\par
\par
value\par
\par
The current value of the filter.\par
\par
To swap in your own Filter Component, use the admin.components.Filter property in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ Field \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const myField: Field = \{\par
  name: 'myField',\par
  type: 'text',\par
  admin: \{\par
    components: \{\par
      Filter: '/path/to/MyCustomFilterComponent', \par
    \},\par
  \},\par
\}\par
All Custom Filter Components receive the same Default Field Component Props.\par
\par
For details on how to build Custom Components themselves, see Building Custom Components.\par
\par
Label\par
The Label Component is rendered anywhere a field needs to be represented by a label. This is typically used in the Edit View, but can also be used in the List View and elsewhere.\par
\par
To swap in your own Label Component, use the admin.components.Label property in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ Field \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const myField: Field = \{\par
  name: 'myField',\par
  type: 'text',\par
  admin: \{\par
    components: \{\par
      Label: '/path/to/MyCustomLabelComponent', \par
    \},\par
  \},\par
\}\par
All Custom Label Components receive the same Default Field Component Props.\par
\par
For details on how to build Custom Components themselves, see Building Custom Components.\par
\par
TypeScript\par
When building Custom Label Components, you can import the component types to ensure type safety in your component. There is an explicit type for the Label Component, one for every Field Type and server/client environment. The convention is to append LabelServerComponent or LabelClientComponent to the type of field, i.e. TextFieldLabelClientComponent.\par
\par
import type \{\par
  TextFieldLabelServerComponent,\par
  TextFieldLabelClientComponent,\par
  // ...and so on for each Field Type\par
\} from 'payload'\par
Description\par
Alternatively to the Description Property, you can also use a Custom Component as the Field Description. This can be useful when you need to provide more complex feedback to the user, such as rendering dynamic field values or other interactive elements.\par
\par
To add a Description Component to a field, use the admin.components.Description property in your Field Config:\par
\par
import type \{ CollectionConfig \} from 'payload'\par
\par
export const MyCollectionConfig: CollectionConfig = \{\par
  // ...\par
  fields: [\par
    // ...\par
    \{\par
      name: 'myField',\par
      type: 'text',\par
      admin: \{\par
        components: \{\par
          Description: '/path/to/MyCustomDescriptionComponent', \par
        \},\par
      \},\par
    \},\par
  ],\par
\}\par
All Custom Description Components receive the same Default Field Component Props.\par
\par
For details on how to build a Custom Components themselves, see Building Custom Components.\par
\par
TypeScript\par
When building Custom Description Components, you can import the component props to ensure type safety in your component. There is an explicit type for the Description Component, one for every Field Type and server/client environment. The convention is to append DescriptionServerComponent or DescriptionClientComponent to the type of field, i.e. TextFieldDescriptionClientComponent.\par
\par
import type \{\par
  TextFieldDescriptionServerComponent,\par
  TextFieldDescriptionClientComponent,\par
  // And so on for each Field Type\par
\} from 'payload'\par
